Latin America in the Fight against the Coronavirus
SÃO PAULO/SANTIAGO/BOGOTÁ/MEXICO CITY – The COVID-19 pandemic is a shock of unprecedented scale and unknown duration.
The consequences are already catastrophic.
If we do not decisively confront the crisis, it could become the most tragic episode in Latin American history.
So far, the political responses in our region have been very diverse.
Some governments reacted quickly and declared the protection of public health their top priority.
Others, however, unfortunately downplayed the dangers of the pandemic, provided their citizens with false information, and ignored not only scientific research but also the advice of their own experts.
These leaders chose, amidst the tragedy, a populist and divisive policy.
Latin America's first priority must be to keep the number of deaths as low as possible.
Policymakers must focus on improving health systems, equipping hospitals with resources, temporarily using underutilized infrastructure such as hotels or conference centers, and significantly increasing testing capacity.
Moreover, Latin American countries must reject export controls on medical supplies and other critical resources and advocate for additional resources for the World Health Organization (WHO) – in stark contrast to US President Donald Trump, who unilaterally froze approximately $500 million in contributions to the WHO.
We need stronger global cooperation among health authorities to increase testing capacity, treat and isolate patients, and develop treatments and vaccines – in order to ultimately end the pandemic.
The economic shock is enormous: not only has Latin American domestic production been disrupted, but the countries there are also suffering from declining export volumes and prices, income losses due to the lack of tourism, fewer remittances, and significant capital outflows.
The supply shock in large parts of the economy could, together with the decline in demand, trigger a contraction spiral.
To prevent this, bold measures are required to protect household incomes.
This means transferring benefits to the victims of the crisis, including informal and independent workers who do not have access to employment subsidies or unemployment insurance.
Reliefs for businesses are also important.
Subsidies that help companies pay their wages and wage-related costs protect both them and their employees during the crisis. Therefore, they are crucial for a rapid economic recovery after the pandemic.
If the flood of insolvencies is not prevented, the next victims of the pandemic could be the banks.
And at that point, the payment system – and with it the entire economy – is at risk.
Many companies, especially small and medium-sized ones, will suffer significant income losses during the crisis.
Without support, the lack of liquidity will soon become a solvency problem.
Tax deferrals, payment postponements, and subsidized loans will not be sufficient.
This emergency requires not only unprecedented loan guarantees by governments to ensure that banks continue to lend, but also temporary regulatory changes to promote credit expansion.
Even well-capitalized and well-managed state banks can play a leading role in this regard.
In general, the measures will differ from country to country, but overall, extraordinary budget resources will be required everywhere to accelerate the recovery.
Governments must stimulate employment and economic activities without worsening the health risks.
The problem is that the fiscal space in Latin America is today even tighter than after the global financial crisis of 2008.
Therefore, the fiscal burdens must be cushioned through budget adjustments in areas of lower priority.
There is a risk of credit rating downgrades, but this can be reduced by the promise of governments to correct higher budget deficits within an appropriate time frame.
However, external support for households and balance of payments is urgently needed – particularly for the small and less developed Latin American countries.
If both private companies and governments run higher deficits, the countries' current account balances are likely to worsen.
The recent capital outflows from emerging countries – one of the largest reversals in the history of financial markets – exacerbate the problem further.
The resulting currency depreciations can have a destabilizing effect.
In many economies in the region, the only way to cope with these mutually reinforcing shocks will be to obtain much more external support.
The IMF plays a crucial role here.
It must take care of the countries' short-term currency and budget needs and continue to support their economies during this crisis, whose duration is highly uncertain.
To do this, it needs more resources and the ability to disburse them quickly.
Latin American governments should jointly call for a revival of the IMF's global reserve currency – the Special Drawing Rights (SDRs), which should reach a volume of one trillion SDRs.
Although SDRs are allocated to member countries according to their IMF quotas, a non-proportional allocation could be achieved by establishing a common pool under the Fund's supervision.
Additionally, the IMF could create the necessary capacity by immediately doubling the volume of new credit agreements to meet the upcoming strong credit demand.
Furthermore, the Fund must, since traditional IMF credit programs are not approved in time, improve access to low-threshold tools with rapid disbursement – such as its Rapid Financing Instrument – or launch new credit facilities for the pandemic.
Large central banks issuing reserve currencies can help by expanding access to currency swaps – either directly or indirectly through the IMF or the Bank for International Settlements, which can channel liquidity to central banks.
Domestically, central banks must use all the instruments at their disposal and, if necessary, create new ones to provide sufficient liquidity to financial markets and the economy.
Finally, multilateral development banks (MDBs) such as the World Bank, the Inter-American Development Bank, and the Latin American CAF Development Bank must double the volume of net credit disbursement in the region and tap into highly liquid global capital markets to provide further fiscal support.
During exceptional circumstances and in countries without market access, official lending could be supplemented by a debt restructuring.
The MEB should also provide countries with guidelines on the different policy areas involved in crisis management, including their own estimates of COVID-19 infection and mortality rates – particularly for countries where governments downplay the health threat.
Time plays a crucial role in this.
The challenge posed by this pandemic is without precedent in recent history.
The world and the Latin American and Caribbean region cannot afford delayed or inadequate responses.
Mutual trust, transparency, and reason remain the best guidelines in these uncertain times – and not populism or demagogy.
The crisis must not be used as an excuse to weaken our hard-earned civil rights.
Instead, it can serve as an opportunity to strengthen democracy in Latin America and show what it can offer its citizens.
